      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Spotting Common-Tile Bingos on Your Rack</h2>
      <p>Recognising a bingo among 7 random tiles takes practice. Here's how to build the skill quickly with common-tile combinations:</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Look for familiar stems first:</span> Scan your rack for SATINE, RETINA, or SALINE. If you spot 5-6 of those letters, you're close. Focus on what the remaining tile(s) can form.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Sort by vowel-consonant:</span> Separate your tiles into vowels (left) and consonants (right). A balanced 3-4 or 4-3 split is prime bingo territory.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Check common endings:</span> Look for -ING, -TION, -ED, -ER, -EST, -IER. Many common-tile bingos end with IEST, INES, AINS, or TERS.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Use the Word Finder for validation:</span> Enter all 7 tiles into our solver. If a bingo exists, it'll appear at the top of the results ranked by score.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

